Claim: if 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is an orthogonal projector, the 
\begin_inset Formula $I-2P$
\end_inset

 is unitary.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is an orthogonal projector 
\begin_inset Formula $P=P^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(I-2P\right)^{\dagger}\left(I-2P\right) & = & \left(I^{\dagger}-2P^{\dagger}\right)\left(I-2P\right)\\
 & = & \left(I-2P\right)\left(I-2P\right)\\
 & = & I-4P-4P^{2}\\
 & = & I-4P-4P\\
 & = & I
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is unitary.
 The geometric intuition is that since 
\begin_inset Formula $I-2P=\left(I-P\right)-P$
\end_inset

 it's the case that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(I-2P\right)x & = & \left(I-P\right)x-Px
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Since in general 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(I-P\right)x+Px$
\end_inset

 it's obvious that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(I-P\right)x+\left(-Px\right)$
\end_inset

 is the reflection of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 across 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{range}\left(I-P\right)$
\end_inset

, which is what unitary transformations are (reflections and/or rotations).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
